  "prompt": "Can Windex leach through aquarium glass?",
  "response": "No, Windex should not leach through aquarium glass.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Glass Impermeability:** Glass is inherently impermeable to liquids and gases, including the components of Windex (water, ammonia, detergents, etc.). Glass is made of a network of silica (silicon dioxide) and other minerals, which forms a dense and non-porous structure.\n*   **Surface Contact:** The issue is not that Windex will go through the glass, it is what is left behind on the glass that could be harmful. The most important thing is to **thoroughly rinse** the glass after cleaning with Windex or any other cleaner to ensure that all residue is removed.\n*   **Aquarium Safety:** When cleaning the *outside* of an aquarium with Windex, it's crucial to prevent the cleaner from getting *inside* the tank. Even trace amounts of ammonia and detergents can be harmful to fish and other aquatic life.\n*   **Safe Practices:** The safest way to clean the *outside* of an aquarium is to spray the Windex on a cloth first, then use the damp cloth to wipe the glass. This minimizes the chance of overspray into the tank. After wiping with the Windex dampened cloth, wipe again with a cloth dampened with water to remove any remaining Windex residue. If you are unsure, it is best to simply use a clean, damp cloth.\n*   **Inside Aquarium Cleaning:** Never use Windex or any household cleaners to clean the *inside* of an aquarium. Algae scrapers or specialized aquarium cleaning tools are designed for this purpose. If you must clean the inside glass, you can use a clean sponge or cloth and plain water. Be sure to rinse everything well before putting it back into the tank.\n\nIn conclusion, glass is impermeable, so Windex won't leach *through* it. However, residue left on the glass *can* be harmful, so thorough rinsing is essential when cleaning the outside of an aquarium. Never use Windex inside the aquarium.",
